# Linux Storage Management Notes (EBS Volume)

## Objective

Learn how to prepare, format, mount, and verify a new storage volume in Linux.

---

## Storage Concepts Learned

### Block Devices

Linux represents disks as block devices under:

```bash
/dev/
```

Examples:

```text
/dev/nvme0n1
/dev/nvme1n1
/dev/nvme2n1
/dev/nvme3n1
```

---

### Filesystem

A new disk cannot be used until a filesystem is created.

Common filesystems:

| Filesystem | Usage                         |
| ---------- | ----------------------------- |
| ext4       | Most common Linux filesystem  |
| xfs        | Enterprise Linux environments |
| vfat       | Cross-platform compatibility  |

---

## Commands Learned

### lsblk

Displays all block storage devices attached to the system.

```bash
lsblk
```

Useful flags:

| Flag | Purpose                       |
| ---- | ----------------------------- |
| `-f` | Show filesystem type and UUID |
| `-o` | Customize displayed columns   |

Examples:

```bash
lsblk -f

lsblk -o NAME,SIZE,FSTYPE,MOUNTPOINT
```

---

### mkfs

Creates a filesystem on a disk.

Syntax:

```bash
sudo mkfs -t <filesystem> <device>
```

Example:

```bash
sudo mkfs -t ext4 /dev/nvme3n1
```

Useful filesystem types:

```bash
sudo mkfs -t ext4 /dev/nvme3n1
sudo mkfs -t xfs /dev/nvme3n1
```

---

### mkdir

Creates a mount point directory.

```bash
sudo mkdir /mnt/ebs-storage
```

Common locations:

```text
/mnt
/media
/data
```

---

### mount

Mounts a filesystem to a directory.

Syntax:

```bash
sudo mount <device> <mountpoint>
```

Example:

```bash
sudo mount /dev/nvme3n1 /mnt/ebs-storage
```

---

### umount

Unmounts a filesystem.

```bash
sudo umount /mnt/ebs-storage
```

or

```bash
sudo umount /dev/nvme3n1
```

---

### df

Displays mounted filesystems and available disk space.

```bash
df -h
```

Useful flags:

| Flag | Purpose              |
| ---- | -------------------- |
| `-h` | Human readable sizes |
| `-T` | Show filesystem type |

Examples:

```bash
df -h
df -Th
```

---

### blkid

Displays filesystem UUID information.

```bash
sudo blkid
```

Example output:

```text
/dev/nvme3n1: UUID="xxxx" TYPE="ext4"
```

Useful when configuring persistent mounts.

---

### file -s

Checks the filesystem present on a device.

```bash
sudo file -s /dev/nvme3n1
```

Example output:

```text
Linux rev 1.0 ext4 filesystem data
```

---

### mount

Displays currently mounted filesystems.

```bash
mount
```

Filter specific devices:

```bash
mount | grep nvme
```

---

## Typical Linux Storage Workflow

### 1. Verify Disk Attached

```bash
lsblk
```

### 2. Create Filesystem

```bash
sudo mkfs -t ext4 /dev/nvme3n1
```

### 3. Create Mount Point

```bash
sudo mkdir /mnt/ebs-storage
```

### 4. Mount Disk

```bash
sudo mount /dev/nvme3n1 /mnt/ebs-storage
```

### 5. Verify Mount

```bash
df -h

lsblk

mount | grep nvme3n1
```

### 6. Test Storage

```bash
cd /mnt/ebs-storage

sudo touch test.txt

ls -l
```

